          <row>
          <entry>6</entry>
          <entry>0</entry>
          </row>
          </tbody>
          </tgroup>
          </table></para>
      <para id="para-00030">What is the median price?</para>
      </problem>
      <solution id="sol-00005">
      <para id="para-00031">Since 33 is odd, the median is the data value at position <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></math>, where <emphasis effect="italic" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml">n</emphasis> is the number of values in the dataset. There are 33 total values, so our formula becomes <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>33</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>17</mn></mrow></math>. That means we want to look for the 17<sup xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml">th</sup> number in the dataset. Counting from the lowest value, we get:
      <table frame="none" summary="." class="unnumbered" id="table-00007">
      <tgroup cols="2">
